Title: Drum (membranophone) component
Description 1: leather pieces- possibly part of leather keeper for a drum; large [[sketch]] piece is 1.7 x 3" & 2.5" thick -  edge is scalloped; it is slit 2/3's of the way to a hole 5 mm diam. there are stitch holes in a circle around hole with diam about 17m; - circular piece is 19mm diam. & 2 mm thick there is a circle of stitch holes just within the edge & it a diam is 17 mm also -  was probably stitch on the larger leather piece as a reinforcement to the hole"
Description 2: These two leather pieces may have been part of a leather keeper for a drum. Leather keepers were used on rope tension drums. The ropes ran up and down along the outside of the drum and the tension could be adjusted by pushing the leather keepers down or pulling them up. These fragments were found in 1971 during excavation of the stone barracks (also known as the short barracks) at Historic Fort Snelling.

Description 2: This clear glass bottle is almost complete. The embossed lettering reads F. Brown Ess of Jamaica Ginger Philada. It was found in 1971 during excavation of the stone barracks (also known as the short barracks) at Historic Fort Snelling. Jamaica Ginger was a 19th century patent medicine. Like other patent medicines, it had a high alcohol content (70% to 80% ethanol by weight) and during the early 20th century it  provided a convenient way to get around Prohibition laws.

Description 1: clear glass bottle fragments #17- 20 are from, a short wide mouth jar with partial raised lettering. #21 is a bottleneck and shoulder fragment. #22-23 are base fragments from a rectangular HEINZ jar. #24 is a bottle neck from a wide mouth jar.
Description 2: These two sherds (317.407.22, 317.407.23) come from a small glass jar. The embossed lettering on the side reads SEPT. 4 1883  HEINZ No. 55. They were found in 1971 during excavation of the stone barracks (also known as the short barracks) at Historic Fort Snelling. In 1869 company founder Henry Heinz packaged his first product, horseradish, in a clear bottle so customers could see the purity of his product. Heinz has been making and selling tomato ketchup, its best known product, since 1876. It isnt clear what was sold in this particular bottle.
Mgmt Notes 1: Short barracks, Sec. 2, cellar rubble fill

Description 1: light green glass jar (complete) E.F. CRISWOLD CO. HORSERADISH on one panel, THIS BOTTLE IS NEVER SOLD on another
Description 2: The embossed lettering on the front of this clear glass jar reads E.F. GRISWOLD Co  HORSERADISH. The lettering on the back reads: THIS BOTTLE IS NEVER SOLD. Title: Jar
Description 1: clear glass bottle fragment 10-12 are from a start, wide-mouth jar, 13 - 14 are bottle necks
Description 2: One of three glass sherds (317.425.10-.12) all come from one small Vaseline jar. The remaining embossed lettering on the jar reads CHES--- VASELI--- MANUFAC---. These sherds were all found in 1971 during excavation of the stone barracks (also known as the short barracks) at Historic Fort Snelling. Vaseline was patented in 1872 by Robert Augustus Chesebrough. His company was Chesebrough Manufacturing Company and was based in Port Amboy, New Jersey. This jar is an example of a kind being made by the late 1880s.
Mgmt Notes 1: Short Barracks, Section 5, cellar fill.

In the 19th century soldiers at Fort Snelling would have had scabbards for their bayonet and officers and musicians would have had scabbards for their swords.

Title: Cut nail
Description 2: These four iron cut nails were found in 1971 during excavation of the stone barracks (also known as the short barracks) at Historic Fort Snelling. They are rectangular in cross section. These examples show the degradation caused by corrosion; the third nail has almost completely disintegrated. Cut nails were machine cut from bars of iron and were used in the initial construction of Fort Snelling (1820-1825). They were very commonly found in the excavation of all the buildings of the fort.

Description 2: These two objects are both made of carved bone. The first piece is circular with a large hole in the center and four smaller holes placed equidistant around the large hole. There are threads inside of the large hole by means of which the disk can be screwed to the second piece. Circular grooves are carved on the face of the disc. The second piece is a bone cylinder 2-1/2 long with grooves carved around the entire length. There is a hole carved in the top and the cylinder is hollowed about halfway through. There is another hole bored at the top on the side. The cylinder has a whistle like appearance. These two object may have been associated with some kind of hand textile production. These objects were found in 1971 during excavation of the stone barracks (also known as the short barracks) at Historic Fort Snelling."

Title: Medicine bottle
Description 1: complete bottle, lt. aqua, possibly a drugstore bottle, 3.1 x .9" x .9" -  body is 4 paneled square shape raised embossed block lettering on each panel "ESSENCE OF PEPPERMINT BY THE KING'S PATENT" [[sketch]]"
Description 2: This complete small bottle was found in 1971 during excavation of the stone barracks (also known as the short barracks) at Historic Fort Snelling. It measures 3.9 by 0.9 by 0.9. The embossed lettering on the sides of the bottle reads Essence Of Peppermint By The Kings Patent. Essence of Peppermint bottles have been found on many archaeological sites in the United States and Canada including other examples at Fort Snelling. Essence of Peppermint was a patent medicine and was patented by a man named John Juniper in 1762. Production continued into the 20th century. This example is undated.
